         <abstract>
            <p>We describe some novel methods to compute the index of any integer relative to a given primitive root of a prime $p$. Our first method avoids the use of stored tables and apparently requires $O(p^{1/2})$ operations. Our second algorithm, which may be regarded as a method of catching kangaroos, is applicable when the index is known to lie in a certain interval; it requires $O(w^{1/2})$ operations for an interval of width $w$, but does not have complete certainty of success. It has several possible areas of application, including the factorization of integers.</p>
          </abstract>
